== Descriptor Feature: Test Suite Context ==

-- Feature Summary --

The "descriptor" feature adds a one-to-one class relationship:
  class D describes A { }   // D is the descriptor class for A
  class A descriptor D { }  // A declares D as its descriptor

Rules:
- The relationship is bidirectional and must be declared on BOTH sides
- One-to-one: D can describe exactly one class; A can have at most one descriptor
- Hierarchy: if B extends A (and A has descriptor DA), B must also declare a
  descriptor DB. DB must be a subtype of DA (not necessarily direct), and DB
  must declare "describes B". DB can be an indirect subtype via intermediate
  classes that don't declare "describes".
- All subclasses of a described class must also declare a descriptor.
- A descriptor subclass that does NOT declare "describes" is valid — it is just
  a plain subclass of the descriptor and describes nothing.
- Polymorphic: class A<T> descriptor DA<T> { } is supported. Type parameter
  substitution is checked: DA<T>.describes must equal A<T> after substitution.
- Constructor: the descriptor instance is the implicit first argument to A.new:
    def d = D.new(); def a = A.new(d);    // or A.new(d, other_args)
- Field access: a.descriptor returns the descriptor instance; its type is the
  declared descriptor type. The field is READ-ONLY (assignment is AssignError).
- Subtype assignment: def d: DA = b.descriptor (b: B, DB extends DA) is valid.
- The -descriptors flag must be passed to v3c to enable the feature.

Error types used in seman tests:
  DescriptorError  - hierarchy/correspondence violations
  TypeError        - type mismatch in assignments or constructor calls
  AssignError      - attempt to assign to the read-only .descriptor field
  UnresolvedMember - .descriptor accessed on a non-class or class without descriptor

-- Seman Tests (seman/) -- Status as of this writing --

  desc00.v3          basic valid mutual declaration
  extends00-04.v3    inheritance with descriptors (valid and error cases)
  non00-04b.v3       non-class types as descriptor/describes (all errors)
  new00-05.v3        constructor type signatures (valid and error cases)
  poly_new00-01.v3   polymorphic constructor (basic cases only)
  field00-08.v3      .descriptor field access and assignment errors
  poly_field00-07.v3 polymorphic .descriptor field access and assignment errors
  corr00-13.v3       correspondence/hierarchy checks (valid and error cases)
  poly_corr00-18.v3  polymorphic correspondence checks

-- Seman Tests Still Missing --

poly_new: Only 2 tests exist (basic instantiation). Need:
  - TypeError when wrong type arg given to poly constructor
      def a = A<int>.new(D<string>.new());  // TypeError
  - TypeError when type arg omitted/inferred wrongly
  - Valid: A.new(d) with type inference from d's type (poly_new01 covers this)

new: Missing error case where descriptor is passed in wrong argument position
  for a class with multiple constructor params beyond the descriptor:
      A.new(0, d) instead of A.new(d, 0)  -- covered by new04, but consider
      more complex signatures.

field: Missing tests for .descriptor on a subclass variable stored in a
  supertype slot:
      def b: A = B.new(DB.new());
      def d: DA = b.descriptor;  // should be valid (declared type is DA)
      def d: DB = b.descriptor;  // TypeError (static type is A, descriptor is DA)

non: Could add tests for type parameters as descriptor targets, e.g.:
      class A<T> descriptor T { }  // T is not a class type -> DescriptorError
      class A describes B<int> { } // instantiated generic: valid or error?

-- Dynamic Tests to Generate (in test/descriptor/*.v3) --

Dynamic tests use //@execute = N (expected return value) or
//@execute = !SomeException (expected exception).

Basic descriptor access:
  - Create an object, read back its descriptor; return a field from the descriptor
  - Verify descriptor identity: pass same descriptor to two objects, check equality
  - Descriptor with fields: descriptor stores metadata, object reads it via .descriptor

Inheritance at runtime:
  - B extends A; access b.descriptor as DB and as DA (upcast)
  - Override descriptor in subclass; verify each class returns its own descriptor type
  - Deep hierarchy (3+ levels): verify each level has the right descriptor

Null and exception behavior:
  - null00.v3 exists: accessing field of null object -> NullCheckException
  - Need: accessing .descriptor on a null reference -> NullCheckException
  - Need: passing null as descriptor to constructor (if that should raise an error
    at runtime or be valid)

Polymorphic at runtime:
  - A<int>.new(D<int>.new()); then access .descriptor, verify it is a D<int>
  - Polymorphic hierarchy: B<T> extends A<T>; verify descriptors at each level
  - Mixed poly/non-poly: DB extends DA<int>; verify static type and value

Descriptor as factory / reflective use:
  - Store an array of descriptor instances; use them to construct objects
  - Descriptor holds type-specific behavior; call a method on .descriptor
  - Compare two descriptors for equality (same descriptor shared across instances)

Exact-type dynamic check:
  - Downcast: (b as B).descriptor should have type DB at runtime
  - Type test: b is B should still work with descriptor present
  - Incorrect cast involving descriptor hierarchy

Constructor argument order:
  - A(x: int) descriptor D: verify A.new(d, 42).x == 42 and .descriptor == d

See also: null00.v3 in this directory for the existing null execution test pattern.
